06312nam a22008895i 9781501730511DE-B159720190920094934.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190920s2018    nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017305117 a10.7591/97815017305112doi  a(DE-B1597)503412  a(OCoLC)1041193639  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aDS740.5.K6bW335 2018 7aHIS0080002bisacsh04a327.51051909/032231 aWang, Yuanchong, eauthor.10aRemaking the Chinese Empire :bManchu-Korean Relations, 1616-1911 /cYuanchong Wang. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource :b4 b&w halftones, 2 maps, 8 charts  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tMaps -- tAcknowledgments -- tNote on Romanization and Conventions -- tChinese and Korean Reign Periods, 1600-1911 -- tIntroduction -- tPart I. KOWTOWING TO OUR GREAT EMPEROR -- t1. CONQUERING CHOSŎN: The Rise of the Manchu Regime as the Middle Kingdom, 1616-43 -- t2. BARBARIANIZING CHOSŎN: The Chosŏn Model and the Chinese Empire, 1644-1761 -- t3. JUSTIFYING THE CIVILIZED The Qing's Contacts with Chosŏn, Annam, and Britain, 1762-1861 -- tPart II. SAVING OUR CHOSŎN -- t4 DEFINING CHOSŎN: Qing China's Depiction of Chosŏn's Status, 1862-76 -- t5. SUPERVISING CHOSŎN: Qing China's Patriarchal Role in Chosŏn, 1877-84 -- t6. LOSING CHOSŎN: The Rise of a Modern Chinese State, 1885-1911 -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tGlossary of Chinese Characters -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aRemaking the Chinese Empire examines China's development from an empire into a modern state through the lens of Sino-Korean political relations during the Qing period. Incorporating Korea into the historical narrative of the Chinese empire, it demonstrates that the Manchu regime used its relations with Chosŏn Korea to establish, legitimize, and consolidate its identity as the civilized center of the world, as a cosmopolitan empire, and as a modern sovereign state.For the Manchu regime and for the Chosŏn Dynasty, the relationship was one of mutual dependence, central to building and maintaining political legitimacy. Yuanchong Wang illuminates how this relationship served as the very model for China's foreign relations. Ultimately, this precipitated contests, conflicts, and compromises among empires and states in East Asia, Inner Asia, and Southeast Asia - in particular, in the nineteenth century when international law reached the Chinese world. By adopting a long-term and cross-border perspective on high politics at the empire's core and periphery, Wang revises our understanding of the rise and transformation of the last imperial dynasty of China. His work reveals new insights on the clashes between China's foreign relations system and its Western counterpart, imperialism and colonialism in the Chinese world, and the formation of modern sovereign states in East Asia. Most significantly, Remaking the Chinese Empire breaks free of the established, national history-oriented paradigm, establishing a new paradigm through which to observe and analyze the Korean impact on the Qing Dynasty.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 20. Sep 2019) 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 4aQing China, Choson Korea, Zongfan, Chinese empire, imperialism, Manchu, Japan, international law, East Asia, Korea, China, nationalism, Sino-Korea, Qing dynasty, Inner Asia, Southeast Asia. 70(DE-601)10438896X0(DE-588)4003846-4aAußenpolitik2gnd 70(DE-601)1044664640(DE-588)4088875-7aQingdynastie2gnd 70(DE-601)1053674270(DE-588)4175047-0aPolitischer Wandel2gnd 70(DE-601)36896955X0(DE-588)4745210-9aChosŏndynastie2gnd 7aHISTORY / Asia / China.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe Gruyter